# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: physical-modeling-synthesis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/digital-waveguide-synthesis] where $y^{+}$ is the right-going wave, and $y^{-}$ is the left-going wave.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/digital-waveguide-synthesis] It can be seen from this representation that sampling the function y at a given position m and time n merely involves summing two delayed copies of its traveling waves.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/digital-waveguide-synthesis] These traveling waves will reflect at boundaries such as the suspension points of vibrating strings or the open or closed ends of tubes.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/digital-waveguide-synthesis] Hence the waves travel along closed loops.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/digital-waveguide-synthesis] Digital waveguide models therefore comprise digital delay lines to represent the geometry of the waveguide which are closed by recursion, digital filters to represent the frequency-dependent losses and mild dispersion in the medium, and often non-linear elements.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/digital-waveguide-synthesis] Losses incurred throughout the medium are generally consolidated so that they can be calculated once at the termination of a delay line, rather than many times throughout.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/digital-waveguide-synthesis] Waveguides such as acoustic tubes are three-dimensional, but because their lengths are often much greater than their diameters, it is reasonable and computationally efficient to model them as one-dimensional waveguides.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/digital-waveguide-synthesis] Membranes, as used in drums, may be modeled using two-dimensional waveguide meshes, and reverberation in three-dimensional spaces may be modeled using three-dimensional meshes.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/digital-waveguide-synthesis] Vibraphone bars, bells, singing bowls and other sounding solids (also called idiophones) can be modeled by a related method called banded waveguides, where multiple band-limited digital waveguide elements are used to model the strongly dispersive behavior of waves in solids.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/digital-waveguide-synthesis] The term "digital waveguide synthesis" was coined by Julius O.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/digital-waveguide-synthesis] Smith III, who helped develop it and eventually filed the patent.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/digital-waveguide-synthesis] A digital waveguide model of an ideal vibrating string having a single point of damping implemented as a two-point average and initialized to random initial positions and velocities at every sample can be shown to be equivalent to the Karplus–Strong algorithm which was developed some years earlier.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/digital-waveguide-synthesis] Stanford University owned the patent rights for digital waveguide synthesis and signed an agreement in 1989 with Yamaha to develop the technology.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/digital-waveguide-synthesis] All early patents have expired and new products based on the technology are appearing frequently.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/digital-waveguide-synthesis] An extension to DWG synthesis of strings made by Smith is commuted synthesis, wherein the excitation to the digital waveguide contains both string excitation and the body response of the instrument.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/digital-waveguide-synthesis] This is possible under the assumption that the string and body are linear time-invariant systems, which is approximately true for typical instruments, allowing the excited body to drive the string, instead of the excited string driving the body as usual.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/digital-waveguide-synthesis] Thus, the string is excited by a "plucked body response".
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/digital-waveguide-synthesis] This means it is unnecessary to model the instrument body's resonances explicitly using hundreds of digital filter sections, thereby greatly reducing the number of computations required for a convincing resynthesis.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/digital-waveguide-synthesis] Prototype waveguide software implementations were done by students of Smith in the Synthesis Toolkit (STK).
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/digital-waveguide-synthesis] The first musical use of the Extended Karplus Strong (EKS) algorithm was in the composition "May All Your Children Be Acrobats" (1981) by David A.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/digital-waveguide-synthesis] Jaffe, followed by his "Silicon Valley Breakdown" (1982).
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/digital-waveguide-synthesis] Since the EKS became understood as a special case of digital waveguide synthesis years later, the piece can now be considered the earliest use of digital waveguide synthesis as well.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/digital-waveguide-synthesis] Related was "A Bicycle Built for Two" by Max Mathews, John Kelly, and Carol Lochbaum at Bell Labs in 1961, which used the Kelly–Lochbaum ladder filter to model the human vocal tract.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/digital-waveguide-synthesis] To distinguish ladder filters from digital waveguide filters, a digital waveguide is defined as a bidirectional delay line at least two samples long over which no scattering occurs.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] A **finite difference** is a mathematical expression of the form *f*(*x* + *b*) − *f*(*x* + *a*).
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Finite differences (or the associated difference quotients) are often used as approximations of derivatives, such as in numerical differentiation.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] There are many similarities between difference equations and differential equations.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Certain recurrence relations can be written as difference equations by replacing iteration notation with finite differences.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] In numerical analysis, finite differences are widely used for approximating derivatives, and the term "finite difference" is often used as an abbreviation of "finite difference approximation of derivatives".
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Finite differences were introduced by Brook Taylor in 1715 and have also been studied as abstract self-standing mathematical objects in works by George Boole (1860), L.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Finite differences trace their origins back to one of Jost Bürgi's algorithms (c.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] 1592) and work by others including Isaac Newton.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] The formal calculus of finite differences can be viewed as an alternative to the calculus of infinitesimals.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Three basic types are commonly considered: *forward*, *backward*, and *central* finite differences.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Depending on the application, the spacing h may be variable or constant.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] The approximation of derivatives by finite differences plays a central role in finite difference methods for the numerical solution of differential equations, especially boundary value problems.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Hence, the forward difference divided by h approximates the derivative when h is small.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] The error in this approximation can be derived from Taylor's theorem.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] However, the central (also called centered) difference yields a more accurate approximation.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] The main problem with the central difference method, however, is that oscillating functions can yield zero derivative.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] If *f*(*nh*) = 1 for n odd, and *f*(*nh*) = 2 for n even, then *f*′(*nh*) = 0 if it is calculated with the central difference scheme.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] This is particularly troublesome if the domain of f is discrete.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Authors for whom finite differences mean finite difference approximations define the forward/backward/central differences as the quotients given in this section (instead of employing the definitions given in the previous section).
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] In an analogous way, one can obtain finite difference approximations to higher order derivatives and differential operators.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Similarly we can apply other differencing formulas in a recursive manner.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] These equations use binomial coefficients after the summation sign shown as ${\textstyle \ {\binom {n}{j}}~.}$ Each row of Pascal's triangle provides the coefficient for each value of j .
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Note that the central difference will, for odd n, have h multiplied by non-integers.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] This is often a problem because it amounts to changing the interval of discretization.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Forward differences applied to a sequence are sometimes called the binomial transform of the sequence, and have a number of interesting combinatorial properties.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Forward differences may be evaluated using the Nörlund–Rice integral.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Higher-order differences can also be used to construct better approximations.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] As mentioned above, the first-order difference approximates the first-order derivative up to a term of order h.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] This can be proven by expanding the above expression in Taylor series, or by using the calculus of finite differences, explained below.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] If necessary, the finite difference can be centered about any point by mixing forward, backward, and central differences.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Sometimes, the low order derivatives of a function may be analytically known, but high order derivatives are not.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] In these cases, the high order derivatives can be approximated by finite difference of low order derivatives, which is often more accurate and numerically more stable than finite difference of the function *f* (*x*) itself.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] This is sometimes called seminumerical differentiation.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Only the coefficient of the highest-order term remains.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] As this result is constant with respect to *x*, any further pairwise differences will have the value 0.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Let *R*(*x*) be a polynomial of degree *m* − 1 where *m* ≥ 2 and the coefficient of the highest-order term be *a* ≠ 0.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Let *S*(*x*) be a polynomial of degree *m*.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] As *ahm* ≠ 0, this results in a polynomial *T*(*x*) of degree *m* − 1, with *ahm* as the coefficient of the highest-order term.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] This identity can be used to find the lowest-degree polynomial that intercepts a number of points (*x*, *y*) where the difference on the *x*-axis from one point to the next is a constant *h* ≠ 0.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] The arithmetic difference is *h* = 3, as established above.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Given the number of pairwise differences needed to reach the constant, it can be surmised this is a polynomial of degree 3.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Solving for *a*, it can be found to have the value 4.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Thus, the first term of the polynomial is 4*x*3.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Solving for *a*, which is −17, the polynomial's second term is −17*x*2.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] It can be found that *a* = 36 and thus the third term of the polynomial is **36*x***.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Without any pairwise differences, it is found that the 4th and final term of the polynomial is the constant −19.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Using linear algebra one can construct finite difference approximations which utilize an arbitrary number of points to the left and a (possibly different) number of points to the right of the evaluation point, for any order derivative.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] This involves solving a linear system such that the Taylor expansion of the sum of those points around the evaluation point best approximates the Taylor expansion of the desired derivative.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Such formulas can be represented graphically on a hexagonal or diamond-shaped grid.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] This is useful for differentiating a function on a grid, where, as one approaches the edge of the grid, one must sample fewer and fewer points on one side.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Finite difference approximations for non-standard (and even non-integer) stencils given an arbitrary stencil and a desired derivative order may be constructed.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] An important application of finite differences is in numerical analysis, especially in numerical differential equations, which aim at the numerical solution of ordinary and partial differential equations.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] The idea is to replace the derivatives appearing in the differential equation by finite differences that approximate them.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] The resulting methods are called finite difference methods.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Common applications of the finite difference method are in computational science and engineering disciplines, such as thermal engineering, fluid mechanics, etc.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] which holds for any polynomial function f and for many (but not all) analytic functions.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] (It does not hold when f is exponential type $\pi$ .
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] This is easily seen, as the sine function vanishes at integer multiples of $\pi$ ; the corresponding Newton series is identically zero, as all finite differences are zero in this case.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Yet clearly, the sine function is not zero.) Here, the expression ${\binom {x}{k}}={\frac {(x)_{k}}{k!}}$ is the binomial coefficient, and $(x)_{k}=x(x-1)(x-2)\cdots (x-k+1)$ is the "falling factorial" or "lower factorial", while the empty product (*x*)0 is defined to be 1.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] In this particular case, there is an assumption of unit steps for the changes in the values of *x*, *h* = 1 of the generalization below.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Note the formal correspondence of this result to Taylor's theorem.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Historically, this, as well as the Chu–Vandermonde identity, $(x+y)_{n}=\sum _{k=0}^{n}{\binom {n}{k}}(x)_{n-k}\,(y)_{k},$ (following from it, and corresponding to the binomial theorem), are included in the observations that matured to the system of umbral calculus.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Newton series expansions can be superior to Taylor series expansions when applied to discrete quantities like quantum spins (see Holstein–Primakoff transformation), bosonic operator functions or discrete counting statistics.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] To illustrate how one may use Newton's formula in actual practice, consider the first few terms of doubling the Fibonacci sequence *f* = 2, 2, 4, ...
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] In analysis with p-adic numbers, Mahler's theorem states that the assumption that f is a polynomial function can be weakened all the way to the assumption that f is merely continuous.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Carlson's theorem provides necessary and sufficient conditions for a Newton series to be unique, if it exists.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] However, a Newton series does not, in general, exist.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] The Newton series, together with the Stirling series and the Selberg series, is a special case of the general difference series, all of which are defined in terms of suitably scaled forward differences.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] The forward difference can be considered as an operator, called the difference operator, which maps the function f to Δ*h*[*f*].
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] This operator amounts to $\Delta _{h}=\operatorname {T} _{h}-\operatorname {I} ,$ where T*h* is the shift operator with step h, defined by T*h*[*f*](*x*) = *f*(*x* + *h*), and I is the identity operator.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] The finite difference of higher orders can be defined in recursive manner as Δ*n* *h* ≡ Δ*h*(Δ*n* − 1 *h*).
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Another equivalent definition is Δ*n* *h* ≡ [T*h* − I]*n*.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Similar Leibniz rules hold for the backward and central differences.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] The expansion is valid when both sides act on analytic functions, for sufficiently small h; in the special case that the series of derivatives terminates (when the function operated on is a finite polynomial) the expression is exact, for *all* finite stepsizes, h .
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Thus T*h* = *e**h* D, and formally inverting the exponential yields $h\operatorname {D} =\ln(1+\Delta _{h})=\Delta _{h}-{\tfrac {1}{2}}\,\Delta _{h}^{2}+{\tfrac {1}{3}}\,\Delta _{h}^{3}-\cdots ~.$ This formula holds in the sense that both operators give the same result when applied to a polynomial.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Even for analytic functions, the series on the right is not guaranteed to converge; it may be an asymptotic series.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] However, it can be used to obtain more accurate approximations for the derivative.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] For instance, retaining the first two terms of the series yields the second-order approximation to *f* ′(*x*) mentioned at the end of the section *§ Higher-order differences*.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] The calculus of finite differences is related to the umbral calculus of combinatorics.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] A large number of formal differential relations of standard calculus involving functions *f*(*x*) thus *systematically map to umbral finite-difference analogs* involving *f*( *x* T−1 *h* ).
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] and hence *Fourier sums of continuum functions are readily, faithfully mapped to umbral Fourier sums*, i.e., involving the same Fourier coefficients multiplying these umbral basis exponentials.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] This umbral exponential thus amounts to the exponential generating function of the Pochhammer symbols.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Thus, for instance, the Dirac delta function maps to its umbral correspondent, the cardinal sine function $\delta (x)\mapsto {\frac {\sin \left[{\frac {\pi }{2}}\left(1+{\frac {x}{h}}\right)\right]}{\pi (x+h)}},$ and so forth.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Difference equations can often be solved with techniques very similar to those for solving differential equations.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] The inverse operator of the forward difference operator, so then the umbral integral, is the indefinite sum or antidifference operator.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] All of the above rules apply equally well to any difference operator as to Δ, including δ and ∇.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] Finite differences can be considered in more than one variable.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] They are analogous to partial derivatives in several variables.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/finite-difference] However, for many classes of functions, the m -th order derivative tensor is sparse, or its off-diagonal blocks may have low rank.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] At first glance, this technique can be viewed as subtractive synthesis based on a feedback loop similar to that of a comb filter for z-transform analysis.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] However, it can also be viewed as the simplest class of wavetable-modification algorithms now known as digital waveguide synthesis, because the delay line acts to store one period of the signal.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] Alexander Strong invented the algorithm, and Kevin Karplus did the first analysis of how it worked.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] Together they developed software and hardware implementations of the algorithm, including a custom VLSI chip.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] They named the algorithm "Digitar" synthesis, as a portmanteau for "digital guitar".
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] This excitation is output and simultaneously fed back into a delay line L samples long.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] The output of the delay line is fed through a filter.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] The gain of the filter must be less than 1 at all frequencies, to maintain a stable positive feedback loop.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] The filter can be a first-order lowpass filter (as pictured).
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] In the original algorithm, the filter consisted of averaging two adjacent samples, a particularly simple filter that can be implemented without a multiplier, requiring only shift and add operations.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] The filter characteristics are crucial in determining the harmonic structure of the decaying tone.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] The filtered output is simultaneously mixed into the output and fed back into the delay line.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] The fundamental frequency (specifically, the lowest nonzero resonant frequency) of the resulting signal is the lowest frequency at which the unwrapped phase response of the delay and filter in cascade is $-2\pi$ .
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] The required phase delay *D* for a given fundamental frequency *F*0 is therefore calculated according to *D* = *F**s*/*F*0 where *F**s* is the sampling frequency.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] The length of any digital delay line is a whole-number multiple of the sampling period.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] In order to obtain a fractional delay often needed for fine tuning the string below JND (Just Noticeable Difference), interpolating filters are used with parameters selected to obtain an appropriate phase delay at the fundamental frequency.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] Either IIR or FIR filters may be used, but FIR have the advantage that transients are suppressed if the fractional delay is changed over time.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] The most elementary fractional delay is the linear interpolation between two samples (e.g., *s*(4.2) = 0.8*s*(4) + 0.2*s*(5)).
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] If the phase delay varies with frequency, harmonics may be sharpened or flattened relative to the fundamental frequency.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] The original algorithm used equal weighting on two adjacent samples, as this can be achieved without multiplication hardware, allowing extremely cheap implementations.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] Z-transform analysis can be used to get the pitches and decay times of the harmonics more precisely, as explained in the 1983 paper that introduced the algorithm.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] A demonstration of the Karplus-Strong algorithm can be heard in the following Vorbis file.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] The algorithm used a loop gain of 0.98 with increasingly attenuating first order lowpass filters.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] The pitch of the note was A2, or 220 Hz.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] Holding the period (= length of the delay line) constant produces vibrations similar to those of a string or bell.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] Increasing the period sharply after the transient input produces drum-like sounds.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] Due to its plucked-string sound in certain modes, Alex Strong and Kevin Karplus conjectured that the Karplus-Strong (KS) algorithm was in some sense a vibrating string simulation, and they worked on showing that it solved the wave equation for the vibrating string, but this was not completed.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] Smith III recognized that the transfer-function of the KS, when viewed as a digital filter, coincided with that of a vibrating string, with the filter in the feedback loop representing the total string losses over one period.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] He later derived the KS algorithm as a special case of digital waveguide synthesis, which was used to model acoustic waves in strings, tubes, and membranes.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] Smith, and in Smith's PhD/EE dissertation.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] Alex Strong developed a superior wavetable-modification method for plucked-string synthesis, but only published it as a patent.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] The first musical use of the algorithm was in the work *May All Your Children Be Acrobats* written in 1981 by David A.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] Jaffe, and scored for eight guitars, mezzo-soprano and computer-generated stereo tape, with a text based on Carl Sandburg's *The People, Yes*.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] The patent was licensed first to Mattel Electronics, which failed as a company before any product using the algorithm was developed, then to a startup company founded by some of the laid-off Mattel executives.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] They never got sufficient funding to finish development, and so never brought a product to market either.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] Eventually Yamaha licensed the patent, as part of the Sondius package of patents from Stanford.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] It is unknown whether any hardware using the algorithm was ever sold, though many software implementations (which did not pay any license fees to the inventors) have been released.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] The Inventors were not specifically credited, though the term "Karplus-Strong Synthesis" is referenced in some of the manuals.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/karplus-strong-string-synthesis] Hardware components capable of Karplus-Strong style synthesis include the Moog Clusterflux 108M, Mutable Instruments Elements and Rings, 4ms Company Dual Looping Delay, 2HP Pluck, Make Noise Mimeophon, Arturia MicroFreak, Non Linear Circuits Is Carp Lust Wrong?, and the Strymon Starlab.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/physical-modelling-synthesis] For example, to model the sound of a drum, there would be a mathematical model of how striking the drumhead injects energy into a two-dimensional membrane.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/physical-modelling-synthesis] In addition, the same concept has been applied to simulate voice and speech sounds.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/physical-modelling-synthesis] In this case, the synthesizer includes mathematical models of the vocal fold oscillation and associated laryngeal airflow, and the consequent acoustic wave propagation along the vocal tract.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/physical-modelling-synthesis] Further, it may also contain an articulatory model to control the vocal tract shape in terms of the position of the lips, tongue and other organs.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/physical-modelling-synthesis] Smith III and others, and the increase in DSP power in the late 1980s that commercial implementations became feasible.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/physical-modelling-synthesis] Yamaha contracted with Stanford University in 1989 to jointly develop digital waveguide synthesis; subsequently, most patents related to the technology are owned by Stanford or Yamaha.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/physical-modelling-synthesis] The first commercially available physical modelling synthesizer made using waveguide synthesis was the Yamaha VL1 in 1994.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/physical-modelling-synthesis] While the efficiency of digital waveguide synthesis made physical modelling feasible on common DSP hardware and native processors, the convincing emulation of physical instruments often requires the introduction of non-linear elements, scattering junctions, etc.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/physical-modelling-synthesis] In these cases, digital waveguides are often combined with FDTD, finite element or wave digital filter methods, increasing the computational demands of the model.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] A **synthesizer** (also **synthesiser** or **synth**) is an electronic musical instrument that generates audio signals.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers typically create sounds by generating waveforms through methods including subtractive synthesis, additive synthesis, and frequency modulation synthesis.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] These sounds may be altered by components such as filters, which cut or boost frequencies; envelopes, which control articulation, or how notes begin and end; and low-frequency oscillators, which modulate parameters such as pitch, volume, or filter characteristics affecting timbre.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers are typically played with keyboards or controlled by sequencers, software or other instruments, and can be synchronized to other equipment via MIDI.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizer-like instruments emerged in the United States in the mid-20th century with instruments such as the RCA Mark II, which was controlled with punch cards and used hundreds of vacuum tubes.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Moog synthesizer, developed by Robert Moog and first sold in 1964, is credited for pioneering concepts such as voltage-controlled oscillators, envelopes, noise generators, filters, and sequencers.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1970, the smaller, cheaper Minimoog standardized synthesizers as self-contained instruments with built-in keyboards, unlike the larger modular synthesizers before it.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1978, Sequential Circuits released the Prophet-5, which used microprocessors to allow users to store sounds for the first time.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] MIDI, a standardized means of synchronizing electronic instruments, was introduced in 1982 and remains an industry standard.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Yamaha DX7, launched in 1983, was a major success and popularized digital synthesis.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Software synthesizers now can be run as plug-ins or embedded on microchips.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 21st century, analog synthesizers returned to popularity with the advent of cheaper manufacturing.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers were initially viewed as avant-garde, valued by the 1960s psychedelic and countercultural scenes but with little perceived commercial potential.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] *Switched-On Bach* (1968)*,* a bestselling album of Bach compositions arranged for synthesizer by Wendy Carlos, took synthesizers to the mainstream.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] They were adopted by electronic acts and pop and rock groups in the 1960s and 1970s and were widely used in 1980s music.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Sampling, introduced with the Fairlight synthesizer in 1979, has influenced genres such as electronic and hip hop music.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Today, the synthesizer is used in nearly every genre and is considered one of the most important instruments in the music industry.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] As electricity became more widely available, the early 20th century saw the invention of electronic musical instruments including the Telharmonium, Trautonium, ondes Martenot and theremin.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the late 1930s, the Hammond Organ Company built the Novachord, a large instrument powered by 72 voltage-controlled amplifiers and 146 vacuum tubes.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1948, the Canadian engineer Hugh Le Caine completed the electronic sackbut, a precursor to voltage-controlled synthesizers, with keyboard sensitivity allowing for vibrato, glissando, and attack control.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1957, Harry Olson and Herbert Belar completed the RCA Mark II Sound Synthesizer at the RCA laboratories in Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The instrument read punched paper tape that controlled an analog synthesizer containing 750 vacuum tubes.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] It was acquired by the Columbia-Princeton Electronic Music Center and used almost exclusively by Milton Babbitt, a composer at Princeton University.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The authors of *Analog Days* define "the early years of the synthesizer" as between 1964 and the mid-1970s, beginning with the debut of the Moog synthesizer, designed by the American engineer Robert Moog.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Moog was composed of separate modules connected by patch cables that generate, shape or control sound.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Moog developed a means of controlling pitch through voltage, the voltage-controlled oscillator.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] This, along with Moog components such as envelopes, noise generators, filters, and sequencers, became standard components in synthesizers.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Around the same period, the American engineer Don Buchla created the Buchla Modular Electronic Music System.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Instead of a conventional keyboard, Buchla's system used touchplates which transmitted control voltages depending on finger position and force.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] However, the Moog's keyboard made it more accessible and marketable to musicians, and keyboards became the standard means of controlling synthesizers.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Moog and Buchla initially avoided the word *synthesizer* for their instruments, as it was associated with the RCA synthesizer; however, by the 1970s, it had become the standard term.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1970, Moog launched a cheaper, smaller synthesizer, the Minimoog.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] It was the first synthesizer sold in music stores, and was more practical for live performance.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] It standardized the concept of synthesizers as self-contained instruments with built-in keyboards.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the early 1970s, the British composer Ken Freeman introduced the first string synthesizer, designed to emulate string sections.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] After retail stores started selling synthesizers in 1971, other synthesizer companies were established, including ARP in the US and EMS in the UK.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] ARP's products included the ARP 2600, which folded into a carrying case and had built-in speakers, and the Odyssey, a rival to the Minimoog.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The less expensive EMS synthesizers were used by European art rock and progressive rock acts including Brian Eno and Pink Floyd.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Designs for synthesizers appeared in the amateur electronics market, such as a design published in *Practical Electronics* in 1973.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] By the mid-1970s, ARP was the world's largest synthesizer manufacturer, though it closed in 1981.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Early synthesizers were monophonic, meaning they could only play one note at a time.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Some of the earliest commercial polyphonic synthesizers were created by the American engineer Tom Oberheim, such as the OB-X (1979).
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1978, the American company Sequential Circuits released the Prophet-5, the first fully programmable polyphonic synthesizer.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Whereas previous synthesizers required users to adjust cables and knobs to change sounds, with no guarantee of exactly recreating a sound, the Prophet-5 used microprocessors to store sounds in patch memory.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] This facilitated a move from synthesizers creating unpredictable sounds to producing "a standard package of familiar sounds".
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The synthesizer market grew dramatically in the 1980s.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] 1982 saw the introduction of MIDI, a standardized means of synchronizing electronic instruments; it remains an industry standard.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] An influential sampling synthesizer, the Fairlight CMI, was released in 1979, with the ability to record and play back samples at different pitches.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Though its high price made it inaccessible to amateurs, it was adopted by high-profile pop musicians including Kate Bush and Peter Gabriel.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The success of the Fairlight drove competition, improving sampling technology and lowering prices.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Early competing samplers included the E-mu Emulator in 1981 and the Akai S-series in 1985.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1983, Yamaha released the first commercially successful digital synthesizer, the Yamaha DX7.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Based on frequency modulation (FM) synthesis developed by the Stanford University engineer John Chowning, the DX7 was characterized by its *harsh*, *glassy* and *chilly* sounds, compared to the *warm* and *fuzzy* sounds of analog synthesis.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The DX7 was the first synthesizer to sell more than 100,000 unitsand remains one of the bestselling in history.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Digital synthesizers typically contained preset sounds emulating acoustic instruments, with algorithms controlled with menus and buttons.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Synclavier, made with FM technology licensed from Yamaha, offered features such as 16-bit sampling and digital recording.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] With a starting price of $13,000, its use was limited to universities, studios and wealthy artists.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Roland D-50 (1987) blended Roland's linear arithmetic algorithm with samples, and was the first mass-produced synthesizer with built-in digital effects such as delay, reverb and chorus.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1988, the Japanese manufacturer Korg released the M1, a digital synthesizer workstation featuring sampled transients and loops.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] With more than 250,000 units sold, it remains the bestselling synthesizer in history.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The advent of digital synthesizers led to a downturn in interest in analog synthesizers in the following decade.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] ReBirth by Propellerhead Software and Reality by Seer Systems, the first software synthesizers that could be played in real time via MIDI, were released in 1997.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1999, an update to the music software Cubase allowed users to run software instruments (including synthesizers) as plug-ins, triggering a wave of new software instruments.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Propellerhead's Reason, released in 2000, introduced an array of recognizable virtual studio equipment.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The market for patchable and modular synthesizers rebounded in the late 1990s.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 2000s, older analog synthesizers regained popularity, sometimes selling for much more than their original prices.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 2010s, new, affordable analog synthesizers were introduced by companies including Moog, Korg, Arturia and Dave Smith Instruments.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The renewed interest is credited to the appeal of imperfect *organic* sounds and simpler interfaces, and modern surface-mount technology making analog synthesizers cheaper and faster to manufacture.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Early synthesizers were viewed as avant-garde, valued by the 1960s psychedelic and counter-cultural scenes for their ability to make new sounds, but with little perceived commercial potential.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] *Switched-On Bach* (1968), a bestselling album of Bach compositions arranged for Moog synthesizer by Wendy Carlos, demonstrated that synthesizers could be more than "random noise machines", taking them to the mainstream.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] However, debates were held about the appropriateness of synthesizers in baroque music, and according to the *Guardian* they were quickly abandoned in "serious classical circles".
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Today, the synthesizer is one of the most important instruments in the music industry, used in nearly every genre.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] It is considered by the authors of *Analog Days* as "the only innovation that can stand alongside the electric guitar as a great new instrument of the age of electricity ...
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Moog was adopted by 1960s rock acts including the Doors, the Grateful Dead, the Rolling Stones, the Beatles, and Keith Emerson.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Emerson was the first major rock musician to perform with the Moog and it became a trademark of his performances, helping take his band Emerson, Lake & Palmer to global stardom.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] According to *Analog Days*, the likes of Emerson, with his Moog performances, "did for the keyboard what Jimi Hendrix did for the guitar".
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] String synthesizers were used by 1970s progressive rock bands including Camel, Caravan, Electric Light Orchestra, Gentle Giant and Renaissance.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The portable Minimoog (1970), much smaller than the modular synthesizers before it, made synthesizers more common in live performance.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Early synthesizers could only play one note at a time, making them suitable for basslines, leads and solos.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] With the rise of polyphonic synthesizers in the 1970s and 1980s, "the keyboard in rock once more started to revert to the background, to be used for fills and atmosphere rather than for soloing".
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Queen included statements in their 1970s album notes specifying that no synthesisers had been used, but added them in their 1980 album *The Game*.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Minimoog took a place in mainstream African-American music, most notably in the work of Stevie Wonder, and in jazz, such as the work of Sun Ra.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the late 1970s and the early 1980s, the Minimoog was widely used in the emerging disco genre by artists including Abba and Giorgio Moroder.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Sampling, introduced with the Fairlight synthesizer in 1979, has influenced all genres of music and had a major influence on the development of electronic and hip hop music.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 1970s, electronic music composers such as Jean Michel Jarre and Isao Tomita released successful synthesizer-led instrumental albums.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] This influenced the emergence of synth-pop from the late 1970s to the early 1980s.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The sequencer-based Roland TB-303 (1981), in conjunction with the Roland TR-808 and TR-909 drum machines, became a foundation of electronic dance music genres such as house and techno when producers acquired cheap second-hand units later in the decade.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The authors of *Analog Days* connect the synthesizer's origins in 1960s psychedelia to the raves and British Second Summer of Love of the 1980s and the club scenes of the 1990s and 2000s.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Gary Numan's 1979 hits "Are 'Friends' Electric?" and "Cars" made heavy use of synthesizers.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] OMD's "Enola Gay" (1980) used distinctive electronic percussion and a synthesized melody.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Soft Cell used a synthesized melody on their 1981 hit "Tainted Love".
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Nick Rhodes, the keyboardist of Duran Duran, used synthesizers including the Roland Jupiter-4 and Jupiter-8.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Chart hits include Depeche Mode's "Just Can't Get Enough" (1981), the Human League's "Don't You Want Me" and works by Ultravox.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 1980s, digital synthesizers were widely used in pop music.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Yamaha DX7, released in 1983, became a pop staple, used on songs by A-ha, Kenny Loggins, Kool & the Gang.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Its E PIANO 1 preset became particularly famous, especially for power ballads, and was used by artists including Whitney Houston, Chicago, Prince, Phil Collins, Luther Vandross, Billy Ocean, and Celine Dion.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Korg M1 presets were widely used in 1990s house music, beginning with Madonna's 1990 single "Vogue".
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers are common in film and television soundtracks.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1969, Mort Garson used a Moog to compose a soundtrack for the televised footage of the Apollo 11 moonwalk, creating a link between electronic music and space in the American popular imagination.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] ARP synthesizers were used to create sound effects for the 1977 science fiction films *Close Encounters of the Third Kind* and *Star Wars*, including the voice of the robot R2-D2.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 1970s and 1980s, synthesizers were used in the scores for thrillers and horror films including *A Clockwork Orange* (1971), *Apocalypse Now* (1979), *The Fog* (1980) and *Manhunter* (1986).
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Brad Fiedel used a Prophet synthesizer to record the soundtrack for *The Terminator* (1984), and the filmmaker John Carpenter used them extensively for his soundtracks.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers were used to create themes for television shows including *Knight Rider* (1982)*, Twin Peaks* (1990) and *Stranger Things* (2016).
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The rise of the synthesizer led to major changes in the music industry, including job displacement, comparable to the 1920s arrival of sound in film, which put live musicians accompanying silent films out of work.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] With its ability to imitate instruments such as strings and horns, the synthesizer threatened the jobs of session musicians by allowing one keyboardist or music programmer to produce the same range of sounds as an entire orchestra.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] For a period, the Moog was banned from use in union work, a restriction negotiated by the American Federation of Musicians (AFM).
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The musician Walter Sear persuaded the AFM that the synthesizer demanded skill, and the category of *synthesizer player* was accepted into the union.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] However, players were subject to "suspicion and hostility" for years.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1982, following a tour by Barry Manilow using synthesizers instead of an orchestra, the British Musicians' Union attempted to ban synthesizers, attracting controversy.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 1980s, a few musicians skilled at programming the Yamaha DX7 found employment creating sounds for other acts.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers generate audio through various forms of analog and digital synthesis.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Oscillators produce waveforms (such as sawtooth, sine, or pulse waves) with different timbres.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Voltage-controlled amplifiers (VCAs) control the volume or gain of the audio signal.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] VCAs can be modulated by other components, such as LFOs and envelopes.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] A VCA is a preamp that boosts (amplifies) the electronic signal before passing it on to an external or built-in power amplifier, as well as a means to control its amplitude (volume) using an attenuator.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The gain of the VCA is affected by a *control voltage* (CV), coming from an envelope generator, an LFO, the keyboard or some other source.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Envelopes control how sounds change over time.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] They may control parameters such as amplitude (volume), filters (frequencies), or pitch.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Low-frequency oscillators (LFOs) produce waveforms used to modulate parameters, such as the pitch of oscillators (producing vibrato).
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Filters remove frequencies from the audio signal, similarly to equalization, to shape sounds.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] They typically include controls to set the point at which frequencies are attenuated, and to add resonance.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Common types include low-pass filters, which remove audio above a specified frequency, and high-pass filters, which do the opposite.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Filters may be controlled with envelopes or LFOs.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Arpeggiators take input chords and convert them into arpeggios.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] They usually include controls for speed, range and mode (the movement of the arpeggio).
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers are often controlled with electronic or digital keyboards or MIDI controller keyboards, which may be built into the synthesizer unit or attached via connections such as CV/gate, USB, or MIDI.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Keyboards may offer expression such as velocity sensitivity and aftertouch, allowing for more control over the sound.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizer clones are unlicensed recreations of previous synthesizers, often marketed as affordable versions of famous musical equipment.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Clones are available as physical instruments and software.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Companies that have sold software clones include Arturia and Native Instruments.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Behringer manufactures equipment modelled on instruments including the Minimoog, Pro-One, and TB-303, and drum machines such as the TR-808.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Other synthesizer clones include the MiniMOD (a series of Eurorack modules based on the Minimoog), the Intellijel Atlantis (based on the SH-101), and the x0x Heart (based on the TB-303).
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Creating clones of older hardware is legal where the patents have expired.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1997, Mackie lost their lawsuit against Behringer as copyright law in the United States did not cover their circuit board designs.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] A **waveguide** is a structure that guides waves by restricting the direction of transmission of energy.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Common types of waveguides include acoustic waveguides which direct sound, optical waveguides which direct light, and radio-frequency waveguides which direct electromagnetic waves other than visible, or near visible, light, like radio waves.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Without the physical constraint of a waveguide, waves would expand into three-dimensional space and their intensities would decrease according to the inverse square law.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] There are different types of waveguides for different types of waves.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] The original and most common meaning is a hollow conductive metal pipe used to carry high frequency radio waves, particularly microwaves.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Dielectric waveguides are used at higher radio frequencies, and transparent dielectric waveguides and optical fibers serve as waveguides for light.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] In acoustics, air ducts and horns are used as waveguides for sound in musical instruments and loudspeakers, and specially-shaped metal rods conduct ultrasonic waves in ultrasonic machining.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] The geometry of a waveguide reflects its function; in addition to more common types that channel the wave in one dimension, there are two-dimensional slab waveguides which confine waves to two dimensions.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] The frequency of the transmitted wave also dictates the size of a waveguide: each waveguide has a cutoff wavelength determined by its size and will not conduct waves of greater wavelength; an optical fiber that guides light will not transmit microwaves which have a much larger wavelength.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Some naturally occurring structures can also act as waveguides.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] The SOFAR channel layer in the ocean can guide the sound of whale song across enormous distances.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Any shape of waveguide can support EM waves.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] However, irregular shapes are difficult to analyse.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Commonly used waveguides are rectangular or circular in cross-section.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] The uses of waveguides for transmitting signals were known even before the term was coined.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] The phenomenon of sound waves guided through a taut wire have been known for a long time, as well as sound through a hollow pipe such as a cave or medical stethoscope.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Other uses of waveguides are in transmitting power between the components of a system such as radio, radar or optical devices.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Waveguides are the fundamental principle of guided wave testing (GWT), one of the many methods of non-destructive evaluation.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] The first structure for guiding waves was proposed by J.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Thomson in 1893, and was first experimentally tested by Oliver Lodge in 1894.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] The first mathematical analysis of electromagnetic waves in a metal cylinder was performed by Lord Rayleigh in 1897.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] For sound waves, Lord Rayleigh published a full mathematical analysis of propagation modes in his seminal work, "The Theory of Sound".
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Jagadish Chandra Bose researched millimeter wavelengths using waveguides, and in 1897 described to the Royal Institution in London his research carried out in Kolkata.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] The study of dielectric waveguides (such as optical fibers, see below) began as early as the 1920s, by several people, most famous of which are Rayleigh, Sommerfeld and Debye.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Optical fiber began to receive special attention in the 1960s due to its importance to the communications industry.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] The development of radio communication initially occurred at the lower frequencies because these could be more easily propagated over large distances.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] The long wavelengths made these frequencies unsuitable for use in hollow metal waveguides because of the impractically large diameter tubes required.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Consequently, research into hollow metal waveguides stalled and the work of Lord Rayleigh was forgotten for a time and had to be rediscovered by others.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Practical investigations resumed in the 1930s by George C.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Southworth at first took the theory from papers on waves in dielectric rods because the work of Lord Rayleigh was unknown to him.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] This misled him somewhat; some of his experiments failed because he was not aware of the phenomenon of waveguide cutoff frequency already found in Lord Rayleigh's work.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Serious theoretical work was taken up by John R.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] This work led to the discovery that for the TE01 mode in circular waveguide losses go down with frequency and at one time this was a serious contender for the format for long-distance telecommunications.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] The importance of radar in World War II gave a great impetus to waveguide research, at least on the Allied side.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] The magnetron, developed in 1940 by John Randall and Harry Boot at the University of Birmingham in the United Kingdom, provided a good power source and made microwave radar feasible.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] The most important centre of US research was at the Radiation Laboratory (Rad Lab) at MIT but many others took part in the US, and in the UK such as the Telecommunications Research Establishment.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] The head of the Fundamental Development Group at Rad Lab was Edward Mills Purcell.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] His researchers included Julian Schwinger, Nathan Marcuvitz, Carol Gray Montgomery, and Robert H.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Much of the Rad Lab work concentrated on finding lumped element models of waveguide structures so that components in waveguide could be analysed with standard circuit theory.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Hans Bethe was also briefly at Rad Lab, but while there he produced his small aperture theory which proved important for waveguide cavity filters, first developed at Rad Lab.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] The German side, on the other hand, largely ignored the potential of waveguides in radar until very late in the war.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] So much so that when radar parts from a downed British plane were sent to Siemens & Halske for analysis, even though they were recognised as microwave components, their purpose could not be identified.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] German academics were even allowed to continue publicly publishing their research in this field because it was not felt to be important.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Immediately after World War II waveguide was the technology of choice in the microwave field.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] However, it has some problems; it is bulky, expensive to produce, and the cutoff frequency effect makes it difficult to produce wideband devices.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Ridged waveguide can increase bandwidth beyond an octave, but a better solution is to use a technology working in TEM mode (that is, non-waveguide) such as coaxial conductors since TEM does not have a cutoff frequency.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] A shielded rectangular conductor can also be used and this has certain manufacturing advantages over coax and can be seen as the forerunner of the planar technologies (stripline and microstrip).
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] However, planar technologies really started to take off when printed circuits were introduced.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] These methods are significantly cheaper than waveguide and have largely taken its place in most bands.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] However, waveguide is still favoured in the higher microwave bands from around Ku band upwards.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] A propagation mode in a waveguide is one solution of the wave equations, or, in other words, the form of the wave.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Due to the constraints of the boundary conditions, there are only limited frequencies and forms for the wave function which can propagate in the waveguide.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] The lowest frequency in which a certain mode can propagate is the cutoff frequency of that mode.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] The mode with the lowest cutoff frequency is the fundamental mode of the waveguide, and its cutoff frequency is the waveguide cutoff frequency.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Propagation modes are computed by solving the Helmholtz equation alongside a set of boundary conditions depending on the geometrical shape and materials bounding the region.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] The usual assumption for infinitely long uniform waveguides allows us to assume a propagating form for the wave, i.e. stating that every field component has a known dependency on the propagation direction (i.e. z ).
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Then, every unknown field is forced to have a form like $U(x,y,z)={\hat {U}}(x,y)e^{-\gamma z}$ , where the $\gamma$ term represents the propagation constant (still unknown) along the direction along which the waveguide extends to infinity.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] The Helmholtz equation can be rewritten to accommodate such form and the resulting equality needs to be solved for $\gamma$ and ${\hat {U}}(x,y)$ , yielding in the end an eigenvalue equation for $\gamma$ and a corresponding eigenfunction ${\hat {U}}(x,y)_{\gamma }$ for each solution of the former.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] The propagation constant $\gamma$ of the guided wave is complex, in general.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] For a lossless case, the propagation constant might be found to take on either real or imaginary values, depending on the chosen solution of the eigenvalue equation and on the angular frequency $\omega$ .
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] In circuit theory, the impedance is a generalization of electrical resistance in the case of alternating current, and is measured in ohms ( $\Omega$ ).
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] A waveguide in circuit theory is described by a transmission line having a length and characteristic impedance.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] In other words, the impedance indicates the ratio of voltage to current of the circuit component (in this case a waveguide) during propagation of the wave.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Impedance matching is important when components of an electric circuit are connected (waveguide to antenna for example): The impedance ratio determines how much of the wave is transmitted forward and how much is reflected.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] In connecting a waveguide to an antenna a complete transmission is usually required, so an effort is made to match their impedances.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] An impedance mismatch creates a reflected wave, which added to the incoming waves creates a standing wave.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Waveguides can be constructed to carry waves over a wide portion of the electromagnetic spectrum, but are especially useful in the microwave and optical frequency ranges.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Depending on the frequency, they can be constructed from either conductive or dielectric materials.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Waveguides are used for transferring both power and communication signals.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Waveguides used at optical frequencies are typically dielectric waveguides, structures in which a dielectric material with high permittivity, and thus high index of refraction, is surrounded by a material with lower permittivity.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] The structure guides optical waves by total internal reflection.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] An example of an optical waveguide is optical fiber.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Other types of optical waveguide are also used, including photonic-crystal fiber, which guides waves by any of several distinct mechanisms.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Guides in the form of a hollow tube with a highly reflective inner surface have also been used as light pipes for illumination applications.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] The inner surfaces may be polished metal, or may be covered with a multilayer film that guides light by Bragg reflection (this is a special case of a photonic-crystal fiber).
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] One can also use small prisms around the pipe which reflect light via total internal reflection —such confinement is necessarily imperfect, however, since total internal reflection can never truly guide light within a *lower*-index core (in the prism case, some light leaks out at the prism corners).
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] An *acoustic waveguide* is a physical structure for guiding sound waves.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Sound in an acoustic waveguide behaves like electromagnetic waves on a transmission line.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Waves on a string, like the ones in a tin can telephone, are a simple example of an acoustic waveguide.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Another example are pressure waves in the pipes of an organ.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] The term *acoustic waveguide* is also used to describe elastic waves guided in micro-scale devices, like those employed in piezoelectric delay lines and in stimulated Brillouin scattering.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] A waveguide (or tube) impose a boundary condition on the wave equation such that the wave function must be equal to zero on the boundary and that the allowed region is finite in all but one dimension.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] An infinitely long cylinder is an example.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Mathematically, any tube with a bulge, where the width of the tube increases, admits at least one non-propagating bound state.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Using the variational principles, Jeffrey Goldstone and Robert Jaffe have shown a tube of constant width with a twist admits a bound state.
[src:physical-modeling-synthesis/waveguide] Sound synthesis uses digital delay lines as computational elements to simulate wave propagation in tubes of wind instruments and the vibrating strings of string instruments.
